# Next.js Styling Consistency Standards

## Context

- Next.js applications often use multiple styling approaches
- Tailwind CSS and Shadcn UI are primary styling tools in our stack
- Consistent styling patterns prevent design fragmentation and technical debt

## Requirements

### Tailwind CSS Implementation

- Use Tailwind utility classes for component styling
- Follow consistent class ordering convention
- Extract common patterns to component classes
- Implement proper responsive design using Tailwind breakpoints

### Shadcn UI Integration

- Use Shadcn UI components as foundational building blocks
- Follow customization patterns using the theming system
- Maintain component API consistency when extending components
- Document component variants and their use cases

### CSS Architecture

- Avoid global CSS except for root-level theme variables
- Use CSS modules or styled-components for component-specific styles
- Implement consistent naming conventions for CSS classes
- Organize CSS imports to prevent specificity conflicts

### Theme Management

- Use CSS variables for theme values (colors, spacing, etc.)
- Implement proper dark mode support using Tailwind's dark mode
- Create consistent color palette with semantic naming
- Document theme override patterns

## Common Pitfalls

- **Inconsistent class ordering**: Different ordering patterns across components
- **Utility overuse**: Not extracting common patterns to component classes
- **Direct style overrides**: Modifying Shadcn components directly instead of using theme
- **Specificity wars**: Using !important or overly specific selectors
- **Undocumented variants**: Custom component variants without proper documentation

## Migration Patterns

- Create utility functions for class composition
- Implement staged migration of legacy styling
- Use design tokens for consistent values
- Document component styling patterns

